<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEACE DIVIDEND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The most frightening concept to come out of Washington recently is the 
so-called "peace dividend," referred to by everyone with a shiny new idea in 
need of a buck. 
</P>
<P>
There exists no dividend with its resulting infusion of cash to liberate a 
budget shackled by huge deficits. 
</P>
<P>
Any savings realized as a result of decreased defense spending are merely 
non-spent dollars that immediately reduce the deficit. The savings are not 
actual hard dollars to be spent on alternative programs. 
</P>
<P>
The crisis of the federal budget is the lack of effective leadership and 
inability of elected representatives to make difficult decisions. The "problem" 
is not a lack of revenues, now approximately a trillion dollars a year. 
</P>
<P>
New programs should be introduced on the basis of value after careful 
consideration, not on the ability of government accountants to perform various 
sleight of hand. 
</P>
<P>
DREW J. PHILLIPS 
</P>
<P>
Carson 
</P>
</TEXT>
