<HEADLINE>
<P>
JAZZ REVIEWS ; 
</P>
<P>
CARMEN MCRAE HITS HER STRIDE AT CATALINA BAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON HECKMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hearing Carmen McRae sing these days is a bit like watching a veteran pitcher 
come to the mound in a tight situation. Both may be a bit creaky getting 
started, missing a target here and there, not quite in control of the 
overpowering talents that got them to the big leagues. 
</P>
<P>
But when the game is on the line, they both come through -- winning because 
winning is what they know best. McRae's opening set at Hollywood's Catalina Bar 
&amp; Grill on Tuesday night was a perfect example of how this master singer 
has adjusted her performing to the inevitable changes that time brings. 
</P>
<P>
Starting somewhat erratically, she moved through standards like "Never Let Me 
Go" and "I Concentrate on You" plagued by little lapses of pitch and emphasis, 
never quite getting to the centers of the songs. It even appeared, for a few 
distressing moments, that her usually dependable skills were being supported by 
sheer instincts alone. 
</P>
<P>
When McRae dug into a sensuously swinging duet with bassist Scott Colley on 
"Get Out of Town," however, she suddenly blossomed to life, a musical phoenix 
rising through the rhythm. Her revival continued with a gorgeous ballad 
interpretation of "More Than You Know" (including the lovely verse) and a 
scat-filled set of variations on "Old Devil Moon." 
</P>
<P>
From that point on, McRae was in her stride. Two more standards, "For All We 
Know" and "Mean to Me," followed -- executed with the precise diction and 
crystal-clear musical focus that have been her stocks in trade for nearly four 
decades. As a final bit of icing on the cake, McRae closed with an attractive 
new song, Brazilian singer-songwriter Djavan's "Upside Down." 
</P>
<P>
Backed by pianist Eric Gunnison, drummer Mark Pulice and bassist Colley, 
McRae's performance was a small gem of musical maturity. She continues at 
Catalina's through Sunday night. DON HECKMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
