<HEADLINE>
<P>
FREEWAY LEAGUE ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
LA HABRA CONTAINS FULLERTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB BORSUM Sonora 54, Troy 35 -- Chris Kiel had 15 points, Casie Lozano 13 
and Denise Donadio 12 to lead host Sonora (4-10, 1-3). Brandy Richardson had 22 
poin 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
La Habra High School's "freak" defense in the second half and Leslie Ferguson's 
27 points and 14 rebounds led the Highlanders over Fullerton, 58-40, in a 
Freeway League girls' basketball game Thursday night at Fullerton High. 
</P>
<P>
Ferguson scored 12 of La Habra's 20 points in the third quarter and its defense 
controlled the boards, forcing Fullerton (11-5 overall, 4-1 in league play) 
into poor shots. 
</P>
<P>
"We put our freak defense, designed to take two shooters (Fullerton's Summer 
McLane and Jennifer Comstock) out of the game while increasing our intensity . 
. . in the second quarter," La Habra Coach John Koehler said. 
</P>
<P>
"As a result, our defense forced the ball into the hands of Fullerton's 
nonshooters and contained them to only one shot, and our rebounders were in 
position to sweep the boards." 
</P>
<P>
La Habra led only 22-18 at halftime, but Fullerton lost momentum when Lynn 
Gilbert, its inside shooter, injured her right ankle with 7:43 to play in half. 
Gilbert injured the same ankle last year and was out for three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
La Habra (13-2, 4-0) had 47 rebounds. Zrinka Kristich had 15 rebounds and 12 
points and Ana Kristrich had 12 rebounds and 13 points. 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton Coach Vernie Ford called her team's poor shooting (15 of 54) 
"discouraging, an age-old problem for us." 
</P>
<P>
"We played hard and made good adjustments, but our shooting just wasn't on 
target," Ford said. 
</P>
<P>
McLane hit six of 15 shots from the field (15 points), and Comstock hit six of 
17, one a three-pointer (13 points). 
</P>
<P>
Koehler said the score is not indicative of the game. "We made mistakes in the 
first half and Fullerton got after us," he said. BOB BORSUM Sonora 54, Troy 35 
-- Chris Kiel had 15 points, Casie Lozano 13 and Denise Donadio 12 to lead host 
Sonora (4-10, 1-3). Brandy Richardson had 22 points for Troy. Sonora trailed, 
15-3, in the first quarter, but came back with a press and took the lead, 
33-31, in the fourth quarter. Sonora made 14 of 18 free throws in the fourth 
quarter and outscored Troy, 40-14, in the second half. Buena Park 55, Sunny 
Hills 30 -- Three girls scored in double figures to lead host Buena Park. 
Melissa Massinsin had 13 points for the winners. Gina Bongiovanni had 11 and 
Daniele Fagins added 10. 
</P>
